to the editor adam cohen editorial observer april 6 suggests that justice sandra day o'connor may vote to uphold the university of michigan 's affirmative action admissions program partly as a result of her inclination to look for herself in the litigants before her judges are influenced by the life experiences they bring to the bench and by the usual biases and prejudices to which no citizen is immune even so they strive to decide cases based on the law and reason particularly now during the filibuster over miguel estrada the public is disserved by reducing our understanding of judicial decision making to the perceived influence of a jurist 's race religion gender or class justice o'connor 's vote in the michigan case will turn less on the interesting historical circumstance that she was the first woman to become a supreme court justice than on her nuanced views of the role of race consciousness in government action marc falkoff brooklyn april 7 2003

